---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import SCorpTaxCalculator from "../../components/SCorpTaxCalculator.astro";
---

<Layout 
  title="S-Corp vs Sole Proprietor Tax Calculator (Free) | TaxDebtWealthSuite"
  description="Compare your tax bill as a sole trader vs S-Corp/Ltd/CCPC/Pty Ltd. Free salary-vs-distribution optimizer for side hustles and freelancers in the US, UK, Canada & Australia."
  ogImage="https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/images/og-s-corp-tax.png"
>
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="x-default" href="https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/s-corp-tax-calculator/" slot="head" />
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="en-us" href="https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/s-corp-tax-calculator/" slot="head" />
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="en-gb" href="https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/s-corp-tax-calculator/uk/" slot="head" />
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="en-ca" href="https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/s-corp-tax-calculator/canada/" slot="head" />
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="en-au" href="https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/s-corp-tax-calculator/australia/" slot="head" />

  <script type="application/ld+json" slot="head">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@graph": [
      {
        "@type": "SoftwareApplication",
        "name": "S-Corp vs Sole Proprietor Tax Calculator",
        "applicationCategory": "FinanceApplication",
        "operatingSystem": "Web",
        "offers": {
          "@type": "Offer",
          "price": "0",
          "priceCurrency": "USD"
        },
        "description": "Compare your tax bill as a sole trader vs S-Corp/Ltd/CCPC/Pty Ltd. Free salary-vs-distribution optimizer for side hustles and freelancers in the US, UK, Canada & Australia."
      },
      {
        "@type": "FAQPage",
        "mainEntity": [{
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "When should I switch from a sole proprietor to an LLC or S-Corp?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "In the US, the general threshold is when net profit consistently exceeds $40,000–$50,000/yr — at that level, corporate tax savings exceed compliance costs (~$1,500–$3,000). In the UK, incorporating as a Limited Company makes sense above approximately £30,000–£35,000. Canadian CCPCs become advantageous at $50,000+ due to the Small Business Deduction (9% blended rate). Australian Pty Ltd structures are cost-effective above $80,000 where the 25% company tax rate beats top personal marginal rates of 45% + 2% Medicare."
          }
        }]
      },
      {
        "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
        "itemListElement": [
          {
            "@type": "ListItem",
            "position": 1,
            "name": "Home",
            "item": "https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/"
          },
          {
            "@type": "ListItem",
            "position": 2,
            "name": "S-Corp Tax Calculator",
            "item": "https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/s-corp-tax-calculator/"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
  </script>

  <main class="flex-grow max-w-7xl w-full mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-6 sm:py-10">
    
    <!-- Title Section -->
    <div class="mb-8 text-center sm:text-left">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight font-sans">
        S-Corp Salary vs Distributions Tax Calculator
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 mt-2 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
        Compare unincorporated vs. incorporated business structures in the US, UK, Canada, and Australia. Run instant break-even compensation audits.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-4 text-xs text-slate-400">
        Switch to another country variant: 
        <span class="text-slate-300 font-semibold">United States (Default)</span> | 
        <a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/uk/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">United Kingdom (Ltd Company)</a> | 
        <a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/canada/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Canada (CCPC)</a> | 
        <a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/australia/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Australia (Pty Ltd)</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Calculator Component -->
    <SCorpTaxCalculator defaultCountry="US" />

    <!-- Explainer Content -->
    <div class="border-t border-slate-800/60 mt-12 bg-gradient-to-b from-slate-950 to-slate-950/95">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-16">
        <section aria-labelledby="corp-guide-heading">
          <div class="mb-6">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-emerald-500/10 text-emerald-400 border border-emerald-500/20 mb-4">Business Tax Strategy</span>
            <h2 id="corp-guide-heading" class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight leading-snug">
              Choosing the Right Side-Hustle Business Structure
            </h2>
            <p class="mt-3 text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Understanding <strong class="text-slate-200">when to switch from sole proprietor to LLC</strong> (or Limited Company) is one of the highest-ROI decisions a self-employed professional can make. The answer depends on your jurisdiction, your net profit level, and the cost of corporate compliance overhead.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-6 text-sm text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <article>
              <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-slate-100 mb-2">The Self-Employment Tax Problem</h3>
              <p>
                Every dollar of profit from a sole proprietorship or sole trader business is subject to both <strong class="text-slate-300">income tax</strong> and <strong class="text-slate-300">self-employment / payroll taxes</strong>. In the US, this means 15.3% SE tax on top of ordinary income rates — effectively a penalty for entrepreneurship that W-2 employees don't pay in full. In the UK, Class 4 National Insurance adds 6% on profits between £12,570 and £50,270. These <strong class="text-slate-300">side hustle tax write offs</strong> are only partial — the SE tax deduction only offsets 50% of the SE tax burden.
              </p>
            </article>
 
            <article>
              <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">2026 Tax Landscape: Sole Trader vs. Corporate Structure Comparison</h3>
              <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-slate-800">
                <table class="w-full text-xs text-left">
                  <thead>
                    <tr class="bg-slate-900 border-b border-slate-800">
                      <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-300 uppercase tracking-wider">Metric</th>
                      <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-400 uppercase tracking-wider">Sole Trader / Self-Employed</th>
                      <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-brand-400 uppercase tracking-wider">S-Corp / Ltd / CCPC / Pty Ltd</th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody class="divide-y divide-slate-800/60">
                    <tr class="hover:bg-slate-900/40 transition-colors">
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-slate-300">🇺🇸 SE / Payroll Tax</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-rose-400">15.3% on all net profit</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-emerald-400">15.3% on salary only (~40% of profit)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="hover:bg-slate-900/40 transition-colors">
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-slate-300">🇬🇧 NI / Corp Tax</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-rose-400">Class 4 NI: 6% (£12,570–£50,270)</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-emerald-400">Corp Tax 19% + 8.75% dividend tax</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="hover:bg-slate-900/40 transition-colors">
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-slate-300">🇨🇦 CPP / Corp Tax</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-rose-400">CPP: 9.9% both sides (up to ~$73,200)</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-emerald-400">CCPC: 9% SBD federal rate</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="hover:bg-slate-900/40 transition-colors">
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-slate-300">🇦🇺 Medicare / Corp Tax</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-rose-400">Medicare levy 2% + marginal income tax</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-emerald-400">Pty Ltd: 25% + franked dividends</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="hover:bg-slate-900/40 transition-colors">
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-slate-300">Setup Cost / yr</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-slate-400">~$0 (no registration needed)</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-slate-400">$1,200–$2,500 (compliance + accountant)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="hover:bg-slate-900/40 transition-colors">
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-slate-300">Break-Even Profit</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-slate-400">Below threshold</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-brand-300 font-semibold">US $40k · UK £30k · CA $50k · AU $80k</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="hover:bg-slate-900/40 transition-colors">
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-slate-300">Liability Protection</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-rose-400">None — personal assets at risk</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-emerald-400">Limited liability shield</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>
            </article>

            <article>
              <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-slate-100 mb-2">Corporate Tax Structure for Freelancers — The Bottom Line</h3>
              <p>
                <strong class="text-slate-300">corporate tax structure for freelancers</strong> becomes compelling when your net profit consistently exceeds the break-even threshold and you have the discipline to run payroll, file corporate returns, and maintain a business bank account. Our <strong class="text-slate-300">Side-Hustle Tax Calculator</strong> above models this comparison in real time for all four jurisdictions — simply enter your revenue, expenses, and day-job income to see your instant break-even analysis. If you are using business profit to clear personal liabilities, map your repayment timeline using our <a href="/debt-payoff-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline font-semibold">debt snowball vs avalanche planner</a>. Alternatively, if you plan to accumulate wealth inside your business and borrow against company assets later, read about the <a href="/buy-borrow-die-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline font-semibold">Buy, Borrow, Die portfolio strategy</a>.
              </p>
            </article>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Accordion -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-amber-500/10 text-amber-400 border border-amber-500/20 mb-4">FAQ</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h3>
            <div class="faq-item border border-[#1E294B] rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-[#141C32]">
              <button
                class="faq-trigger w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer"
                aria-expanded="false"
                onclick="this.setAttribute('aria-expanded', this.getAttribute('aria-expanded')==='true' ? 'false' : 'true'); this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden');"
              >
                <span class="text-sm font-semibold text-white pr-4">When should I switch from a sole proprietor to an LLC or S-Corp?</span>
                <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 flex-shrink-0 transition-transform duration-200 group-[&[aria-expanded=true]]:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
                </svg>
              </button>
              <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6">
                <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
                  In the <strong class="text-slate-300">US</strong>, the general threshold is when net profit consistently exceeds <strong class="text-slate-300">$40,000–$50,000/yr</strong> — at that level, corporate tax savings exceed compliance costs (~$1,500–$3,000). In the <strong class="text-slate-300">UK</strong>, incorporating as a Limited Company makes sense above approximately <strong class="text-slate-300">£30,000–£35,000</strong>. <strong class="text-slate-300">Canadian</strong> CCPCs become advantageous at <strong class="text-slate-300">$50,000+</strong> due to the Small Business Deduction (9% blended rate). <strong class="text-slate-300">Australian</strong> Pty Ltd structures are cost-effective above <strong class="text-slate-300">$80,000</strong> where the 25% company tax rate beats top personal marginal rates of 45% + 2% Medicare.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
